    <title>Combined summary - Package Relay Proposal</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T21:03:47.917899+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-June/020542.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin Core developer Gloria Zhao has proposed a new protocol called "Package Relay" to improve the efficiency of transaction relay in the Bitcoin network. The proposal aims to create a more fee-based market for block space and addresses the issue of pinning attacks. The package relay protocol is defined by a set of rules to be followed when relaying packages between nodes. The proposal suggests creating a package relay that would bundle multiple transactions together and send them as a single unit across the Bitcoin network. This would make it difficult for attackers to target specific transactions and overwhelm the network with excessive data requests. However, there are potential issues with package relay such as pinning attacks and package-feerate downgrades attacks that need to be addressed.In the email thread, the conversation focuses on the implementation of package relay in Bitcoin, specifically version 1 and potential improvements for version 2. The sender clarifies that version 1 is only meant to solve one of two use cases, with orphan-fetching being added as an afterthought. Version 2 could include a "pckginfo2" message containing a transaction with all of its ancestors. Rules are defined for packages such as "Only 1 child with unconfirmed parents" and "Total fees and weight". New messages have been added to the protocol to support package relay, including "sendpackages", "getpckgtxns", and "pckgtxns". Clients implementing this protocol will only attempt to send and request packages if agreed upon during the version handshake. The proposal is backward compatible with older clients and clients using BIP330 reconciliation-based transaction relay.Tom Trevethan inquired about the availability of submitpackage RPC on mainnet in the current core release via bitcoin-dev mailing list. He also enquired about any plans or timeline for its deployment in the next release. Greg replied stating that a PR was opened, with caveats, to address this concern and provided a link to it. Additionally, he shared a link for higher level tracking of the project.The email thread discusses potential issues with peer-to-peer package announcements and proposes solutions. Concerns about dishonest peers announcing packages with incorrect information are addressed by providing fee and weight information when announcing a package and encoding parent transactions as short hashes of the wtxid. The feasibility of making ancestor/descendant limits configurable in package relay and the possibility of using batch transactions more generally are also debated.Overall, the conversation suggests that there are potential issues with package relay, but with further consideration, it could be a useful addition to Bitcoin's protocol. The proposal aims to improve the mempool and miner policy, making it easier for users to fee-bump their transactions and secure contracting protocols. The proposal builds upon previous work by other developers, including Suhas Daftuar and Antoine Riard. Zhao hopes to receive feedback on the proposal from other Bitcoin developers and acknowledges the contributions of John Newbery, Martin Zumsande, Matt Corallo, Christian Decker, David Harding, Antoine Poinsot, Antoine Riard, Gregory Sanders, Chris Stewart, and Bastien Teinturier in the development of the proposal. A list of related links and resources is provided at the end of the proposal.</summary>
